        Sunshine Gal

        19th November 2024
        0
        Vote score

        here's a recent review of FLO'S debut album by rolling stone magazine *my personal rankings though, i couldn't post the actual RS link*. so rolling stone ranks the album around a C to a C+ rating...(i feel it should be a perfect rating. i just wish 'trustworthy' was a full track...def. would've made the album a more fun mix with a lush ballad in with the all upbeat/uptempo songs. so if they release a deluxe version later on, i HIGHLY recommend making 'trustworthy' a full track)

        so to me, this is a fair review & 1 thing rolling stone couldn't stop mentioning was their lush vocals...which is non-stop throughout the entire album :)))))) here are the stand out tracks in my opinion:

        1. on & on *I swear, i can't stop dancing @ work every time i listen to this song.* THIS song takes you right back to the 2000s music scene here in the states: ashanti, mariah, aaliyah, beyonce, destiny's child, janet jackson, jennifer lopez, alicia keys all made songs like this! great times!

        2. IWH2BMX *i would hate to be my ex*: great beats, def. a club hit! def. a reincarnation of beyonce's 2008 'single ladies' theme. takes me back to mariah's 2005 album 'emancipation of mimi' & tracks like 'shake it off' & 'it's like that'.

        3. nocturnal: i think the song should a be a little longer, def. a re-visit to beyonce's 2003 debut album 'dangerously in love'. dangerous beats on this one, watch out LOL!

        4. bending my rules: here the girls lush vocals REALLY stand out. ear candy throughout the song.

        5. soft: same with 'bending my rules'...the girls just sound soooo good LOL! can't say it any other way. (you'll see why rolling stone kept mentioning over and over how good they sound together).

        6. shoulda woulda coulda: as far as i know, this is all 3 girls' fave track. hot beats & hot vocals on this one.

        7. in my bag: this is their current single with u.s. female rapper glorilla...again, songs like this would be the #1 & top 10 smashes over here in the 2000s. another song with dangerous beats, you can't stop bopping to this song. also check out their vid!

        8. how does it feel?: great beats & ear candy vocals...can't say it any other way.

        9. AAA *access all areas*: here the girls lush vocals shine practically all throughout the song. gets you ready for more fun all throughout the album.

        didn't want to make this review too long...the whole album is fantastic! the girls really knocked it out the park & i see why it took them a lil' longer to release this album. i'm glad they took their time....you just keep hearing the quality in the songs every single time you listen to them no matter how many times you have it on repeat. *goes to show they got it right!*. treat yourself to this album! ok here's the rolling stone review: *i can't paste the link*, google 'are FLO the next great girl group?' by rolling stone.

        Chart Review 15/11/24

        I don't have anything creative to say this week. However, I may or may not be hibernating from the comment section for the next couple of weeks. This is due to the fact that I've been roped into spending a fortnight in the Canary Islands for my 18th birthday, and I'm unsure as to whether or not there's gonna be Wi-Fi in my hotel. Hopefully there will be, but at least it can give me a break from moaning about how stale the charts are these days if there isn't any. See you in seven days. Maybe.


        AMAZING TIER:

        Chappell Roan [4] (New No.1 lads. In my chart anyway.), Linkin Park [25] (That album impact is gonna be ruthless.), Shaboozey [26] (Make that 30 weeks for America's No.1 for the past million months.)

        GREAT TIER:

        Chappell Roan [17], Sabrina Carpenter [19], Adam Port/Stryv/You Get The Drill By Now [11]

        GOOD TIER:

        Billie Eilish [13], Sabrina Carpenter [10], Tate McRae [36], Mariah Carey [38] (To be fair, it's the only Christmas song you'd catch me singing at the top of my lungs. ), Gracie Abrams [31] (This was last in the Top 40 TWENTY-TWO WEEKS AGO. WHY IS IT BACK NOW. It's alright.), Sonny Fodera/Jazzy/D.O.D. [34]

        OK TIER:

        ROS ft. Bruno Mars [3], Tyler, The Creator [27], Addison Rae [16], Chrystal [39], (Hooray for minimalism I guess.), Gracie Abrams [1], Teddy Swims [5], Billie Eilish [7] (Nothing like a Billie ballad to re-affirm your sense of boredom eh?), Lady Gaga [21], Myles Smith [12]

        EH TIER:

        Gigi Perez [2], Gracie Abrams [20], Sabrina Carpenter [6], KSI ft. Trippie Redd [9], Paris Paloma [22] (I didn't care about this when it first charted, and my opinion hasn't altered since. Blame Donald Trump.), Noah Kahan [32], Morgan Wallen [40], One Direction [28]

        DISLIKE TIER:

        Lady Gaga & Bruno Mars [14], Teddy Swims [8] (Good for you I s'pose.), Myles Smith [24] (New one is better lolz.), The Kid LAROI [30], Dasha [37]

        BAD TIER:

        The Weeknd/Playboi Carti [15], Hozier [33], BL3SS/CamrinWatsin/bbyclose [35]

        AWFUL TIER:

        cass/RAYE/D-Block Europe [29] (I've had enough of this muck.), Benson Boone [18] (Where's Wham! when you need them?), Teddy Swims [23]


        EVERYTHING THAT'S NEW THIS WEEK:

        Myles Smith - Nice To Meet You [12] (Considering how Stargazing just does not want to evaporate anytime soon, seeing him break his 1-hit wonder status with a song that isn't as monotonous is... reassuring I guess.)

        Griff - last night's mascara [57] (Still yet to make anything as good as Black Hole, but you know, at least she's trying. To be fair, she can still chart these days despite her recent singles flopping like crazy.)

        Zach Bryan - High Road [66] (Just 4 months after his latest album, the mid-table country sleeper-agent sticks a couple songs out and hopes for the best. This is fine or whatever who cares.)

        Zach Bryan - This World's a Giant [73] (And here's the other one. If this was George Ezra recording this he'd be No.1 for months. It's also the best thing Zach's made so far. See guys? I don't DESPISE country or anything...)

        Tyla - PUSH 2 START [74] (And in other news, South Africa's finest is still very much known for Water and nothing else outside of the Afrobeat community. This single isn't gonna change that I'm afraid.)

        Don Toliver - No Pole [82] (A song from the deluxe version of his 2023 album goes on viral on TikTok. Nuff said really.)

        Lola Young - Messy [87] (Took you long enough to have Top 100 success. Even though it feels like a boygenius B-side to my ears.)

        PARTYNEXTDOOR - Dreamin [88] (This is Drake album filler, which is probably the worst criticism you give a trap song in 2024.)

        Jazzy/KILIMANJARO - No Bad Vibes [94] (Ireland's answer to Becky Hill desperately attempts to hang out with Adam Port. The results are grim, let me tell you.)

        SIENNA SPIRO - MAYBE. [100] (If you told me that this first apperance for the latest balladeer to give us headaches was on the new John Lewis ad, I'd probably believe you. Shame some creep called Sam Clegg is there instead.)


        Farewell for now pop-pickers.
